No-Show Appointment Prediction

Introduction

No-shows costs billions to healthcare systems across the world, in the US alone, they account for $150 billion wasted every year.

This kernel will train on historical data using predictive modelling to determine if a client will show up or not for an appointment.

## Plot Correlation dataframe
corrplot(cor.data, method = 'color')

## correlogram helps to visualize variables that are highly correlated (i.e A full pie chart equals a perfect correlation)
corrgram(show.raw.data, order=TRUE, lower.panel = panel.shade, upper.panel = panel.pie, text.panel = panel.txt)

The Correlation plot are usefull for identifying linear relationships. In this scenario, the interesting pattern about Status is that no varible appears to have a linear relationship. Apart from this, we can see correlations between age, Hipertension, and diabetes. Another interesting variable is SMS_received.

Lets start by looking how Age behaves in regards to Status.

Age seems to influence positively the occurence of our target variable (Status) in age groups of 10~40 years and negative influence on groups of anything above, hence its near zero correlation. Lets split into age groups to have a closer look.

The groups above 90 years should be disregarded in the analysis, given the small amount of observations, other than that we can observe how ages ranging between 10 and 20 are almost twice as likely to miss a medical appointment than somebody within the range of 60 to 70 years old.

Another interesting finding is the NA group, they are the result of trying to assign age of 0 to groups and represent missing data.

sum(show.raw.data$Age == 0)
## [1] 3539

Next, well have a look at SMS_received variable:

By evaluating SMS alongside Age, we see an interesting pattern, where sending SMS actually increases the likelihood of a patient not showing, such effect is more prominent on age groups 10~40.

Next, well look at how Neighbourhood influences:

The neighbourhood seems to have an effect with no shows, another deep dive analysis could to use this information to engineer the distance traveled to the medical exam, maybe offer transportation service to their appointments.

As we would expect, gender alone doesnt really play any role on predicting our target variables. The next two plots will give us an outlook of the Scholarship variable

Scholarship has an interesting effect on no shows, it appears that people with such variable are more prone to not showing on a medical exam. Scholarship in this dataset actually refers to a social wellfare program of the Brazilian goverment that aids poor families - it gave the suspition that an income related variable could play an interesting role in predicting no shows.

Predictive Modeling

Feature Engineering to clean some variables

#===============================================================
# [1] Predictive Modeling # 1: Support Vector Machine (SVM)
#===============================================================
# Remove unecessary columns, change var types to factor

showtime3 <- show.raw.data


showtime3$AwaitingTime2<-abs(showtime3$AwaitingTime2)

showtime3$Sex <-ifelse(showtime3$Gender =="F", 1, 0)
is.numeric(showtime3$Sex)
## [1] TRUE
showtime3$Status<- as.factor(showtime3$Status)
showtime3$Visit<- ifelse(showtime3$Status == "Yes", 1, 0)

is.numeric(showtime3$Visit)
## [1] TRUE
#showtime3$AppointmentDay <-  as.POSIXlt(showtime3$ApointmentDay)

#showtime3$ApointmentMonth <- month(showtime3$ApointmentData,label = TRUE)
#as.numeric(showtime3$ApointmentMonth)
showtime3$AwaitingTime2 <- as.numeric(showtime3$AwaitingTime2)
is.numeric(showtime3$AwaitingTime2)
## [1] TRUE
#check data frame for missing data and insert 0 value insted of NA
showtime3[is.na(showtime3)] <-0
## Warning in `[<-.factor`(`*tmp*`, thisvar, value = 0): invalid factor level,
## NA generated
### choose random sample for data
data.sample <- sample_n(showtime3, 200)
data.sample$Visit <- factor(data.sample$Visit)
#select columns to use for prediction
data.sample.use <- data.sample %>% select(1:13,15,19,20)


#split the data to train and test sets
set.seed(1234)
sample <- sample.split(data.sample.use$Visit,0.7)
# 70% of data = train 
train <- subset(data.sample.use, sample==T)
# 30% = test
test <- subset(data.sample.use, sample==F)


#TRAIN SVM
#model.one <- svm(Visit ~ Age+Sex+AwaitingTime2, data = train)
#summary(model.one)

# Tune Parameters
tuned.results <- tune(svm,train.x = Visit ~ Age+Sex+AwaitingTime2, data = train, kernel ='radial',ranges = list(cost=c(100,200),gamma=c(0.1)))
print(summary(tuned.results))

# [3] Predictive Modeling #3: Using LINEAR REGRESSION
#=============================================================================================================================================
# Build the Model to train on the variables 
set.seed(1234)
df.lm <- showtime3 %>% select(PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received, AwaitingTime2, Visit)

# Split up sample
sample.lm <- sample.split(df.lm$Visit, SplitRatio = 0.7)
# 70% of data = train 
train.lm <- subset(df.lm, sample==TRUE)
# 30% of data = test 
test.lm <- subset(df.lm, sample==FALSE)

# Train and Build the Model
model.lm <- lm(Visit ~ ., data = train.lm)
summary(model.lm)

# Interpretation
# Note: FOr most regressions, you want the residuals to look like a Normal Distribution when you plot it. 
# Estimate - Is the value of slope calculated by the regression.  
# Std. Error - Is a measure of the variability in the Estimate of the Coefficients. Rule of thumb, value must be less than the Coefficient Estimate. lower the better
# t Value -  Is a score that measures whether or not the coefficient for the variable is meaningful for the model.
# Probability or P value - Is the probability that the variable/column is not relevant or signifcant. You want it as small as possible. The more star the more significance. 

# Also, R Squared value is a metric for evaluating the 'Goodness of Fit' of the model. Higher is better with 1 being the best. High R squared indicates good correlation but Correlation is not always Causation. 

# Plot the Residuals
